    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-28T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-28T20:00:00-05:00" n="393"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.52/440a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hayes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-28T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 28, 1944—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1193. Department’s 1153 of April 25. On assumption that agreement will be reached
                    with Spaniards on wolfram, clarification in respect to the initial loading of
                    petroleum products is necessary. The <pb facs="0417" n="407" xml:id="pg_407"/>
                    policy of the Department is to permit resumption of petroleum shipments on same
                    basis in effect prior to suspension of petroleum shipments. However, shipments
                    at even this rate will be reconsidered if Spain does not lift present
                    restrictions on consumption once shipments arrive in Spain. It is not intended
                    that inventories should be appreciably increased over present levels.</p>
                <p>The following policy is for your guidance in releasing tankers for the initial
                    loading date: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Bulk petroleum products shipments, exclusive of bulk luboils and
                            aviation gasoline, are not to exceed 14,000 tons for any one loading
                            date. See Department’s 27, January 4.<note n="22" xml:id="d393fn1">Not
                                printed.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Bulk luboils can be loaded up to 4100 tons or an average loading for
                            the <hi rend="italic">Campilo.</hi>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Bulk 87 octane aviation gasoline shall not exceed 320 tons, the
                            monthly quota allowed in the aviation gasoline agreement.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Only one tanker loaded crude oil or gas oil at any one loading elate
                            in 1943 for the Canary Islands. Consequently, permission to load crude
                            oil or gas oil should be initially granted to only one of the CEPSA<note
                                n="23" xml:id="d393fn2">Compañía Española de Petróleos, Sociedad
                                Anónima.</note> tankers <hi rend="italic">Gerona, Gobeo, or
                                Zaragoza.</hi>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The policy in respect to packaged petroleum products will be outlined in a
                    subsequent cable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
